        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Boston&#44; Nov. 26&#44; 1885.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#44; Sarah<lb/> Harris&#44; has arrived all right<lb/> and I have got her in a good<lb/> situation&#44; and I will look after<lb/> her as well as I do to my own<lb/> daughter. I hope that your deeds<lb/> and my own will be carried<lb/> out in good shape. May the<lb/> Almighty God help you in<lb/> every shape &#94; and manner for ever and<lb/> ever&#44; for this&#44; for what you have<lb/> done&#44; Is not a simple thing&#44; to<lb/> &#94; take out a <sic>jewis</sic> child out of the hands<lb/> of Christian. As I am only a<lb/> poor man and if I would have<lb/> another chance like it I would<lb/> spend the last cent for such a<lb/>case.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I give you my word of honor as<lb/> a man&#44; that I will be to this<lb/> girl as a father to a child.<lb/></p>
            <p>I remain yours truly&#44; S. Bloom.<lb/></p>
            <p>15 Morton St.<lb/>
                Boston&#44;<lb/>
                Mass.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
